{\plain }{\plain\f17 The interrupt topics can be accessed with search keys (see }{\uldb {\f17 Search Facilities}}{\v HHsearch}{\plain\f17 ) or from the }{\uldb {\f17 main index}}{\v contents}{\plain\f17  via sub indexes.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f17 The appearance of sub indexes depends on some configuration file settings and program options at compile time. The following text describes the default appearence. See }{\uldb {\f17 Compile Time Configuration}}{\v HHcompilation}{\plain\f17  for other posibilities.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f17 The main index's "Interrupt Index" entry takes you to either a }{\uldb {\f17 compressed index}}{\v idInterrupts}{\plain\f17  or to an }{\uldb {\f17 expanded index}}{\v idIndex}{\plain\f17 . Each of them have a hotspot at the top causing the other one to pop up and to be the one selected from the main index.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f17 The compressed index has references to a subindex for each interrupt number, for example to }{\uldb {\f17 INT 03 - CPU-generated - BREAKPOINT}}{\v 03_0}{\plain\f17 . The subindexes have references to the individual interrupt topics.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f17 The expanded index has direct references to each individual interrupt topic.\par 
\par 
}{\plain\f17 Many interrupt topics have references to }{\uldb {\f17 tables}}{\v HHtable}{\plain\f17 , always of the form "#nnnn" where nnnn is a four digit decimal number. Clicking on these hotspots causes the table to pop up in a separate window, so it is easy to switch between the two topics. Tables can have references to other tables, and if such a hotspot is selected in the secondary (table) window, the current window is erased and the new table is drawn. To ease cross referencing between two tables, use the first table's hotspot "Copy to Main" to have it pop up in the main window before selecting the referenced table.\par 
